{
  "doc_id": "14842",
  "text": "However, the perturbative evaluation of the excitation rate has a restricted domain of applicability. It works best for macroscopic detectors, i.e., systems that leave a macroscopic record (a click) for every particle detection. For such detectors, the perturbative transition rate applies at all times, provided that the detector's temporal resolution is sufficiently large [CITATION_1] . UDW detectors are not macroscopic particle detectors [CITATION_2] , but rather microscopic field probes: localized quantum systems-like for example, elementary particles, nuclei, or atoms-that interact with a quantum field. Information about the field is incorporated in the final state of the probe and is extracted through a suitable measurement [CITATION_3] . In the case of quantum probes, the leading-order perturbative evaluation of the transition rate applies only during very early times, since it ignores the effect of spontaneous emission after excitations. It also ignores the effect of the the back-action of the field to the detector. In order to take these effects into account, the UDW detectors should be treated as open quantum systems [CITATION_4] , with the quantum field playing the role of the environment, inducing dissipation and decoherence.",
